LeetCode 560. Subarray Sum Equals K
Problem:
Given an integer array nums and an integer k, return the total number of subarrays whose sum equals k.

1. Brute Force
Idea

Try every possible subarray and compute its sum.

Algorithm
Fix start index i
Expand end index j
Keep running sum
If sum == k → count++
Time Complexity
O(n²)
Space Complexity
O(1)

Code
class Solution {
    public int subarraySum(int[] nums, int k) {

        int n = nums.length;
        int count = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {

            int sum = 0;

            for (int j = i; j < n; j++) {

                sum += nums[j];

                if (sum == k) {
                    count++;
                }
            }
        }

        return count;
    }
}

2. Prefix Sum (Better but still O(n²))
Idea

Use prefix sum to avoid recomputing sums repeatedly.

Formula
sum(i..j) = prefix[j] - prefix[i-1]
Time Complexity
O(n²)
Space Complexity
O(n)
Code
class Solution {
    public int subarraySum(int[] nums, int k) {

        int n = nums.length;
        int[] prefix = new int[n];

        prefix[0] = nums[0];

        for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
            prefix[i] = prefix[i - 1] + nums[i];
        }

        int count = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            for (int j = i; j < n; j++) {

                int sum = prefix[j] - (i > 0 ? prefix[i - 1] : 0);

                if (sum == k) {
                    count++;
                }
            }
        }

        return count;
    }
}

3. Optimal Solution (Prefix Sum + HashMap)
⭐ Key Insight

We want:

sum(i..j) = k

Using prefix sums:

prefix[j] - prefix[i] = k

Rearrange:

prefix[i] = prefix[j] - k
Idea

While iterating:

Maintain running prefix sum
Check how many times (prefixSum - k) has occurred before
HashMap Meaning
map[prefixSum] = frequency of this prefix sum
Algorithm

Start with:

map = {0:1}
sum = 0
count = 0
For each number:
update sum
check sum - k
add frequency to answer
update map
Time Complexity
O(n)
Space Complexity
O(n)

Code (Optimal)
class Solution {
    public int subarraySum(int[] nums, int k) {

        HashMap<Integer, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();

        map.put(0, 1);

        int sum = 0;
        int count = 0;

        for (int num : nums) {

            sum += num;

            if (map.containsKey(sum - k)) {
                count += map.get(sum - k);
            }

            map.put(sum, map.getOrDefault(sum, 0) + 1);
        }

        return count;
    }
}
Dry Run
nums = [1,1,1], k = 2
i	num	sum	sum-k	count from map	total
0	1	1	-1	0	0
1	1	2	0	1	1
2	1	3	1	1	2

Answer = 2

Why This Works

We are basically counting:

how many previous prefix sums = current_sum - k

Each match represents a valid subarray ending at current index.

Pattern Recognition
This is a classic:
👉 Prefix Sum + HashMap Problem
Core Formula
prefix[j] - prefix[i] = k
→ prefix[i] = prefix[j] - k
When to use this pattern
Subarray sum problems
Count number of subarrays
Continuous range sum
Negative numbers present (important)
